WEBVTT

00:06.402 --> 00:09.989
We’ve come 
to our principal talk


00:09.988 --> 00:15.826
for this 141st class of Gilead,


00:15.827 --> 00:18.039
the graduation.


00:18.038 --> 00:22.291
And we’re going to invite 
Brother Gerrit Lösch now. 


00:22.292 --> 00:25.545
I thought you’d find this interesting.


00:25.545 --> 00:28.840
This is the 141st class.


00:28.840 --> 00:31.968
We’ve heard that throughout 
the morning.


00:31.968 --> 00:35.000
Well, 100 classes ago,


00:39.852 --> 00:44.649
Brother Lösch was graduating 
from the 41st class.


00:44.648 --> 00:46.650
And I don’t know if heaven did it,


00:46.650 --> 00:49.570
but we had an Austrian in each one of those.


00:49.570 --> 00:52.698
So that’s very nice.


00:52.698 --> 00:55.616
And I don’t want to say anything, 
but he is getting a little older,


00:55.617 --> 00:58.954
but he still looks great, doesn’t he?


00:58.953 --> 01:01.206
Because he knew the sister in this class


01:01.207 --> 01:04.710
when she was just a tiny little girl.


01:04.710 --> 01:06.712
So very nice.


01:06.712 --> 01:11.000
And Brother Lösch gave me that information; 
so it’s bona fide.


01:12.635 --> 01:14.720
So Brother Lösch is going to speak


01:14.720 --> 01:18.000
on the theme 
“Make Good Use of Your Time.”


01:20.892 --> 01:25.647
What’s the time?
Well, anyway, it’s time to start.


01:25.647 --> 01:28.817
There are certain things
of which the richest


01:28.817 --> 01:32.570
and the poorest person on earth
have the same:


01:32.570 --> 01:37.533
number one, life;
second, two parents;


01:37.533 --> 01:40.036
third, free will;


01:40.037 --> 01:44.124
and fourth, time.


01:44.123 --> 01:48.211
Poor and rich
all have 24 hours a day.


01:48.212 --> 01:51.049
Therefore,
it’s not quite correct to say


01:51.048 --> 01:54.175
one has “no time” or “plenty of time.”


01:54.175 --> 01:57.595
All have the same—24 hours.


01:57.595 --> 02:01.975
The word “time” is 
an integral part of our vocabulary.


02:01.975 --> 02:03.977
What is time?


02:03.977 --> 02:07.564
Some say, “Time is money.”


02:07.563 --> 02:12.568
If we make decisions,
“time will tell” whether they are good ones.


02:12.568 --> 02:16.073
In the world,
some make wrong decisions and then,


02:16.073 --> 02:21.078
therefore, they have to “do time” in prison.


02:21.078 --> 02:24.998
When driving a car,
we may “make good time,” 


02:24.998 --> 02:29.628
although from “time to time,”
we may stop and have a snack.


02:29.628 --> 02:34.508
We are “taking our time”
if we do not hurry.


02:34.508 --> 02:39.430
We may still arrive “on time”
or even “ahead of time”


02:39.430 --> 02:41.890
if we “time it right.”


02:41.890 --> 02:45.018
But “at times,” we may still be late,


02:45.018 --> 02:47.938
especially if our “timing” was poor,


02:47.938 --> 02:51.000
which may not be “all the time,”
just “from time to time.”


02:54.110 --> 02:56.488
After we arrive at our destination,


02:56.488 --> 03:01.000
the “time has arrived” 
to have a “good time.”


03:02.410 --> 03:04.663
But on a more serious note,


03:04.663 --> 03:08.375
how does the Bible use the term “time”?


03:08.375 --> 03:11.170
Ecclesiastes 3:1 says:


03:11.170 --> 03:14.172
‘There is an appointed time for everything,


03:14.172 --> 03:17.719
‘a time for every activity under the heavens:


03:17.718 --> 03:20.886
‘for birth and for death;


03:20.887 --> 03:23.474
‘to plant, to uproot;


03:23.473 --> 03:26.810
‘to tear down, to build up;


03:26.810 --> 03:29.312
‘to weep and to laugh;


03:29.312 --> 03:32.190
‘to wail and to dance;


03:32.190 --> 03:36.445
a time to keep and a time to throw away,’


03:36.445 --> 03:40.698
like when we have to move 
to another complex.


03:40.698 --> 03:44.411
It is now 
the “acceptable time” to preach


03:44.412 --> 03:47.414
because “the appointed times
of the nations”


03:47.413 --> 03:52.000
are over and we are living
in “the time of the end.”


03:53.045 --> 03:55.547
Therefore, we should be zealous


03:55.547 --> 03:58.675
in line with the urgency of times.


03:58.675 --> 04:01.678
Jehovah blesses the work
and said that he


04:01.678 --> 04:05.265
“will speed it up in its own time.”


04:05.265 --> 04:08.643
The Greek adjective ai·oʹni·os can,


04:08.643 --> 04:10.978
as is evident from the context,


04:10.978 --> 04:15.000
signify both “long lasting”
and “everlasting.”


04:16.652 --> 04:18.654
From the first man, Adam,


04:18.653 --> 04:21.781
forward, time has been measured
in terms of years.


04:21.782 --> 04:25.994
Thus, Adam was 130 years old


04:25.993 --> 04:29.581
when he became father to Seth.


04:29.582 --> 04:32.500
Monthly divisions 
also came into use.


04:32.500 --> 04:35.878
By the time of the Flood,
we find time divided


04:35.878 --> 04:39.006
into months of 30 days,


04:39.007 --> 04:41.760
and a period of five months


04:41.760 --> 04:45.763
is shown in the Bible to equal 150 days.


04:45.763 --> 04:47.765
The same record


04:47.765 --> 04:51.000
also indicates that Noah
divided the year into 12 months.


04:52.938 --> 04:57.191
To track time,
a calendar is used for dividing time


04:57.192 --> 05:01.112
into years, months, weeks, and days.


05:01.112 --> 05:03.157
The world’s oldest calendar


05:03.157 --> 05:07.077
was discovered in a Scottish field


05:07.077 --> 05:09.245
at Warren Field,


05:09.245 --> 05:14.000
according to BBC News
from the year 2013


05:14.000 --> 05:19.130
and National Geographic
of July 15, 2013.


05:19.130 --> 05:24.000
It was excavated first
in the year 2004 only.


05:25.178 --> 05:29.683
To track time during the day,
also, sundials were invented.


05:29.683 --> 05:31.685
They are considered the first 


05:31.685 --> 05:34.730
time-measuring devices known to man.


05:34.730 --> 05:37.440
Dating to the 19th dynasty,


05:37.440 --> 05:41.068
or the 13th century before our Common Era,


05:41.068 --> 05:44.948
a few years ago, a sundial was found


05:44.948 --> 05:47.616
on the floor of a workman’s hut


05:47.617 --> 05:50.537
in the Valley of Kings,


05:50.537 --> 05:54.000
the burial place of rulers from Egypt.


05:55.917 --> 06:00.422
In 1675,
King Charles II of England


06:00.422 --> 06:03.134
commissioned that a small observatory


06:03.133 --> 06:05.843
be constructed in what is now


06:05.843 --> 06:08.555
the London borough
of Greenwich


06:08.555 --> 06:12.392
in order to find out 
the longitude of places


06:12.392 --> 06:17.314
for perfecting navigation
and astronomy.


06:17.313 --> 06:19.650
Two newly invented timepieces


06:19.650 --> 06:23.487
with pendulums 13 feet,
or 4 meters, long


06:23.487 --> 06:26.865
were installed
to make accurate calculations


06:26.865 --> 06:29.618
of the earth’s rotation.


06:29.618 --> 06:33.580
Noon Greenwich Mean Time
is the moment


06:33.580 --> 06:37.918
when the sun reaches
its zenith over any point


06:37.918 --> 06:41.713
on the Greenwich longitude line, 
or meridian, 


06:41.713 --> 06:46.175
from Latin meridianus, of midday.


06:46.175 --> 06:49.805
Based on this Latin word,
time before noon


06:49.805 --> 06:52.307
came to be known as ante meridiem,


06:52.307 --> 06:54.977
or before midday;


06:54.977 --> 06:56.979
and time after noon


06:56.978 --> 07:00.731
came to be known as post meridiem,


07:00.732 --> 07:04.000
or p.m., as we call it.


07:05.320 --> 07:09.617
Today, time is measured
for accuracy with atomic clocks.


07:09.617 --> 07:12.995
They are regulated
by atomic vibrations


07:12.995 --> 07:18.875
and are accurate to one second
in 80 million years


07:18.875 --> 07:21.878
—very accurate.


07:21.878 --> 07:23.880
Again, what is time?


07:23.880 --> 07:25.923
You have heard the saying


07:25.923 --> 07:28.343
“as time goes by”


07:28.343 --> 07:32.263
or “time flies,”


07:32.263 --> 07:36.351
but this is Scripturally
not quite correct.


07:36.352 --> 07:41.189
Time does not go
or walk or fly


07:41.188 --> 07:43.650
—we fly.


07:43.650 --> 07:49.488
And this is supported
at Psalm 90:10,


07:49.488 --> 07:54.076
where Moses wrote this psalm,
not David.


07:54.077 --> 07:57.497
And it says in verse 10:


07:57.497 --> 08:00.542
“The span of our life is 70 years,


08:00.542 --> 08:03.629
“or 80 if one is especially strong.


08:03.628 --> 08:06.631
“But they are filled
with trouble and sorrow;


08:06.632 --> 08:08.467
“they quickly pass by,


08:08.467 --> 08:12.637
and away we fly”


08:12.637 --> 08:14.639
—not the time.


08:14.638 --> 08:16.641
When a man dies,


08:16.642 --> 08:20.000
time is still there
and hasn’t flown anywhere.


08:21.647 --> 08:24.315
Again, what is time?


08:24.315 --> 08:26.610
Twelve o’clock noon in New York


08:26.610 --> 08:32.698
is twelve o’clock midnight
in Mongolia.


08:32.698 --> 08:35.118
When you cross
the date line westbound,


08:35.118 --> 08:37.620
suddenly you have lost
a day, seemingly.


08:37.620 --> 08:41.290
But did you really lose a day?
No.


08:41.290 --> 08:43.335
It’s just the perception.


08:43.335 --> 08:45.378
To the contrary,


08:45.378 --> 08:48.173
when you come
from Japan to the United States,


08:48.173 --> 08:50.800
you seem to gain a day


08:50.800 --> 08:53.678
crossing the date line eastbound.


08:53.678 --> 08:57.765
But does this change the reality of time?
No.


08:57.765 --> 09:02.000
You have not become a day younger.
Sorry.


09:03.605 --> 09:08.193
What’s the time on North Pole,
exactly on North Pole?


09:08.193 --> 09:13.198
If you stay on the North Pole,
does time move on?


09:13.198 --> 09:15.241
Something to think about.


09:15.242 --> 09:19.872
Really, time is an abstract concept
that humans have invented


09:19.872 --> 09:24.000
to explain, compare,
and measure what we observe.


09:25.710 --> 09:30.340
Sometimes, time seems to move
faster than at other times.


09:30.340 --> 09:34.343
There’s an old saying
that “a watched kettle never boils.”


09:34.343 --> 09:36.430
It’s true that when


09:36.430 --> 09:39.182
we are watching time,
when we are conscious of it,


09:39.182 --> 09:41.769
when we are waiting
for something to happen,


09:41.768 --> 09:45.271
then it seems to pass ever so slowly.


09:45.272 --> 09:47.274
However, if we are busy,


09:47.273 --> 09:51.528
if we are interested in and preoccupied
with what we are doing,


09:51.528 --> 09:55.573
then it really appears that time flies.


09:55.573 --> 09:58.535
Moreover, with older people,
time seems to pass


09:58.535 --> 10:02.497
much more quickly
than with young children.


10:02.497 --> 10:04.665
And why is this?


10:04.665 --> 10:07.377
One year added to the life
of a one-year-old


10:07.377 --> 10:10.505
means a 100-percent increase.


10:10.505 --> 10:13.175
One year added to the life
of a 50-year-old


10:13.175 --> 10:17.720
means just 2 percent more.


10:17.720 --> 10:21.683
The perception of time
is also subject to circumstances.


10:21.683 --> 10:23.810
When a couple in love meets,


10:23.810 --> 10:28.982
they wish time would stand still,
is it not so?


10:28.982 --> 10:33.279
But they cannot slow down
what is perceived as time.


10:33.278 --> 10:36.280
On the other hand,
when somebody is sick in a hospital bed,


10:36.280 --> 10:40.035
he might wish that time would pass
more quickly


10:40.035 --> 10:43.788
so he could recover
sooner and go home sooner.


10:43.788 --> 10:48.125
But he cannot speed up
the passing of time.


10:48.125 --> 10:52.088
Time is an observed phenomenon
by means of which


10:52.088 --> 10:54.215
we humans sense and record


10:54.215 --> 10:58.512
changes in our environment
and in the universe.


10:58.512 --> 11:00.722
In the universe,
time is measured


11:00.722 --> 11:05.435
based on the speed of light,
which is a constant.


11:05.435 --> 11:09.563
The Michelson-Morley experiment,
around the end of the 19th century,


11:09.563 --> 11:12.650
discovered that the speed of light
is the same


11:12.650 --> 11:16.487
regardless of the direction
it’s heading


11:16.487 --> 11:19.282
and regardless of the motion


11:19.282 --> 11:22.785
of the originating source.


11:22.785 --> 11:25.288
Light moves at about 


11:25.288 --> 11:30.126
300,000 kilometers per second.


11:30.127 --> 11:34.755
It takes about 100,000 years
for a beam of light


11:34.755 --> 11:39.760
to travel from just one end
of our Milky Way to the other end.


11:39.760 --> 11:41.972
And our Milky Way


11:41.972 --> 11:47.000
is said to have
200 billion stars like the sun.


11:48.603 --> 11:50.771
What you see


11:50.772 --> 11:55.152
when you look up at night
to the night sky,


11:55.152 --> 11:57.695
it’s not what is there now,


11:57.695 --> 12:00.323
but what was there in the past.


12:00.323 --> 12:04.618
When a light beam from a star
that is a million light years away


12:04.618 --> 12:06.621
hits the earth,


12:06.622 --> 12:09.082
it means that the object
that you now see


12:09.082 --> 12:13.504
was there a million years ago.


12:13.503 --> 12:16.213
To see what is there now


12:16.213 --> 12:18.966
and whether the star even still exists,


12:18.967 --> 12:21.595
you need to wait another million years


12:21.595 --> 12:24.597
until the light beam
from that place arrives at the earth.


12:24.597 --> 12:26.600
Just imagine!


12:26.600 --> 12:32.000
Looking at the universe,
we always look only into the past.


12:33.063 --> 12:35.900
It is estimated that the visible universe


12:35.900 --> 12:38.487
exists for 13 billion years.


12:38.487 --> 12:41.155
Most scientists agree that it
had a beginning, 


12:41.155 --> 12:43.533
so-called big bang.


12:43.533 --> 12:45.535
The Bible says:


12:45.535 --> 12:49.872
“In the beginning God created,”
and that includes the visible universe.


12:49.872 --> 12:53.627
The universe expands in all directions.


12:53.627 --> 12:57.880
Scientists have not found an end
of the visible universe


12:57.880 --> 13:00.967
with optical telescopes
or radio telescopes.


13:00.967 --> 13:05.972
But if one would continue
to travel through space long enough,


13:05.972 --> 13:10.977
logically one should come
to an area where there are no more


13:10.977 --> 13:14.689
stars or galaxies, just empty space.


13:14.688 --> 13:19.068
Some known galaxies
are moving into that empty space,


13:19.068 --> 13:23.238
or toward that empty space,
with about the speed of light.


13:23.238 --> 13:25.700
It’s very impressive.


13:25.700 --> 13:29.745
Some scientists say,
“Time does not exist.”


13:29.745 --> 13:33.833
It exists, however,
definitely in our perception.


13:33.833 --> 13:36.251
Man invented
the concept of time


13:36.252 --> 13:40.257
to be able to
measure changes.


13:40.257 --> 13:43.217
Did time always exist?


13:43.217 --> 13:48.097
Well, in Jude 25,


13:48.097 --> 13:52.019
we can read what
it says there


13:52.018 --> 13:54.436
from our own Bible.


13:54.437 --> 13:56.439
It says:


13:56.438 --> 14:00.026
“To the only God our Savior
through Jesus Christ our Lord,


14:00.027 --> 14:03.112
“be glory, majesty,
might, and authority


14:03.112 --> 14:06.032
“for all past eternity


14:06.032 --> 14:10.120
“and now and into all eternity.


14:10.120 --> 14:12.747
Amen.”


14:12.747 --> 14:15.209
Well, we know Jehovah
had no beginning.


14:15.208 --> 14:19.086
We have a hard time
grasping that.


14:19.087 --> 14:23.340
When Jehovah was alone
before he created the Logos,


14:23.340 --> 14:27.762
there was no change,
because Jehovah does not change.


14:27.762 --> 14:32.767
This helps us to understand
in what way Jehovah always existed.


14:32.767 --> 14:35.354
Jehovah is not subject to time.


14:35.353 --> 14:37.771
He exists independently
and outside


14:37.772 --> 14:41.192
from what we
perceive as time.


14:41.192 --> 14:43.654
Where the New World Translation


14:43.653 --> 14:47.740
translates “past eternity,”
in Jude 25, 


14:47.740 --> 14:49.825
the Greek original text


14:49.825 --> 14:54.080
says “before all time.”


14:54.080 --> 14:57.375
Surprise, surprise—before time.


14:57.375 --> 15:02.297
The conclusion is
that time had a beginning. 


15:02.297 --> 15:05.342
Is this a new understanding?
No.


15:05.342 --> 15:07.927
If you want to put down
a reference,


15:07.927 --> 15:12.057
Watchtower, 1982, September 1—


15:12.057 --> 15:16.685
September 1, page 22,
and paragraph 17.


15:16.685 --> 15:19.563
It says about this verse
in Jude 25:


15:19.563 --> 15:22.691
“Jude appropriately
ascribed glory, majesty,


15:22.692 --> 15:24.944
“might and authority
to Jehovah


15:24.943 --> 15:27.113
‘for all past eternity,’”


15:27.113 --> 15:29.573
or to quote The Watchtower,


15:29.573 --> 15:33.410
“‘before all time,’


15:33.410 --> 15:37.832
as men might know it.”


15:37.832 --> 15:40.210
We seem safe to say


15:40.210 --> 15:42.670
that time as we know it,
as humans,


15:42.670 --> 15:44.672
came into being when Jehovah


15:44.672 --> 15:48.092
started to create first the Logos.


15:48.092 --> 15:50.262
But what we perceive
as time now


15:50.262 --> 15:54.000
will continue forever
and ever in the future.


15:55.475 --> 15:58.812
At 1 Corinthians 7:29,
it says:


15:58.812 --> 16:03.817
“Moreover, this I say, brothers,
the time left is reduced.”


16:03.817 --> 16:06.694
Christ had given his disciples


16:06.693 --> 16:09.030
the sign of his presence
and had warned them:


16:09.030 --> 16:11.782
“Keep on the watch, therefore,
because you do not know


16:11.782 --> 16:14.119
on what day
your Lord is coming.”


16:14.118 --> 16:18.665
—Matthew 24:3, 42.


16:18.665 --> 16:21.877
The time left was “reduced”


16:21.877 --> 16:25.839
in the sense that those
first-century Christians


16:25.838 --> 16:30.676
had to live constantly
in expectation of Christ’s coming.


16:30.677 --> 16:32.679
Furthermore, they did not know


16:32.678 --> 16:35.806
how much time remained
for them individually


16:35.807 --> 16:39.060
before “time and unforeseen occurrence”


16:39.060 --> 16:42.397
brought their life to a close.


16:42.397 --> 16:47.402
As an important event nears,
there’s an increased sense of urgency.


16:47.402 --> 16:50.364
How can we illustrate that?


16:50.363 --> 16:52.990
Well, suppose there’s a wedding.


16:52.990 --> 16:57.453
The days before are very busy
in order to prepare well for the event.


16:57.453 --> 17:01.415
Even on the wedding day,
the bride will be urgently preparing herself


17:01.415 --> 17:05.043
so the wedding party
does not have to wait,


17:05.043 --> 17:08.380
which would be very impolite.


17:08.380 --> 17:11.968
If you have to catch a flight,


17:11.968 --> 17:15.430
you are perhaps urgently and nervously
preparing your luggage,


17:15.430 --> 17:19.183
making sure that you
are at the airport on time


17:19.183 --> 17:23.311
because you do not want
to miss the flight.


17:23.312 --> 17:27.109
Suppose a farmer has
a mature crop ready to be harvested.


17:27.108 --> 17:30.026
Suddenly, there is a storm warning.


17:30.027 --> 17:34.157
Dark clouds
loom at the horizon.


17:34.157 --> 17:37.577
The storm could destroy the crop.


17:37.577 --> 17:40.289
Don’t you think
that he’ll urgently organize


17:40.288 --> 17:42.540
his whole household
to go out to the field


17:42.540 --> 17:45.502
and begin to bring in the crop


17:45.502 --> 17:48.504
before the storm hits?


17:48.503 --> 17:51.173
Christians are involved
in a harvesting work.


17:51.173 --> 17:54.343
John 4:35 quotes Jesus, saying:


17:54.343 --> 17:57.638
‘View the fields,
that they are ripe for harvesting.’


17:57.638 --> 18:00.808
The harvest time
will soon be over.


18:00.808 --> 18:04.270
So are we making good use
of our time


18:04.270 --> 18:07.315
to help bring in the harvest?


18:07.315 --> 18:10.735
“The harvest is great,
but the workers are few,”


18:10.735 --> 18:13.738
said Jesus.—Matthew 9:37.


18:13.738 --> 18:16.781
And that shows the urgency.


18:16.782 --> 18:21.787
The hurricane
of the great tribulation is close!


18:21.787 --> 18:26.792
It’s a hurricane in the illustration,
so we need to hurry.


18:26.792 --> 18:30.672
When a woman
is close to giving birth


18:30.672 --> 18:34.634
and the birth pangs started
—the water broke, let’s say—


18:34.633 --> 18:37.095
then it is urgent
to rush her to the hospital


18:37.095 --> 18:41.098
or call a midwife
to come to the home.


18:41.098 --> 18:43.685
Jesus’ death was 
a much more important event


18:43.685 --> 18:47.230
than a wedding, a birth,
a flight, or a crop.


18:47.230 --> 18:50.983
As the appointed time
for Jesus’ sacrificial death


18:50.983 --> 18:54.945
drew near,
his sense of urgency increased.


18:54.945 --> 18:58.240
Jesus stepped up his activity
and his preaching


18:58.240 --> 19:03.245
as the time for him
to be on earth ran out.


19:03.245 --> 19:07.917
True Christians have always lived
with a sense of urgency.


19:07.917 --> 19:12.380
In the first century,
Christians in Judea and Jerusalem


19:12.380 --> 19:14.632
needed to “keep on the watch,”


19:14.632 --> 19:18.260
and that was imperative
because Jesus warned


19:18.260 --> 19:22.140
that the Roman armies
would come and would attack the city.


19:22.140 --> 19:23.640
And he said:


19:23.640 --> 19:26.310
“Let those in Judea
begin fleeing to the mountains.”


19:26.310 --> 19:27.728
It was urgent!


19:27.728 --> 19:30.230
Now more than ever,
the time that remains


19:30.230 --> 19:32.983
before Jehovah
destroys false religion


19:32.983 --> 19:37.113
through political elements is reduced.


19:37.113 --> 19:39.365
It is vital, then,
that we make


19:39.365 --> 19:43.618
wise use of our time
—the time that remains.


19:43.618 --> 19:44.620
How?


19:44.620 --> 19:47.873
As the apostle Paul explains
in Ephesians 5:16,


19:47.873 --> 19:52.836
we must ‘buy out the opportune time’
for “the more important things”


19:52.837 --> 19:57.425
at the expense of what is nonessential.


19:57.425 --> 20:00.302
We need to make every day count.


20:00.302 --> 20:03.472
Do we live as though the end 
could come at any time,


20:03.472 --> 20:06.059
or do we live
as though it is far off?


20:06.058 --> 20:07.851
Jesus warned:


20:07.852 --> 20:10.397
“The Son of man
is coming at an hour that you


20:10.397 --> 20:16.277
do not think to be it.”
—Matthew 24:44.


20:16.277 --> 20:21.115
Our pattern of life reflects
how much we trust in Jehovah


20:21.115 --> 20:23.785
by putting faith
in his prophetic Word,


20:23.785 --> 20:27.747
keeping the urgency
of the times in mind.


20:27.747 --> 20:31.584
Avoid a complacent attitude,


20:31.583 --> 20:35.045
like the people
of Sodom and Gomorrah had.


20:35.045 --> 20:40.050
‘They were eating, drinking, buying,
selling, planting, building,’ said Jesus.


20:40.050 --> 20:42.637
‘But on the day that Lot came out of Sodom,


20:42.637 --> 20:46.640
‘it rained fire and sulfur from heaven 
and destroyed them all.’


20:46.640 --> 20:50.352
—Luke 17:28, 29.


20:50.352 --> 20:52.564
It was urgent for Lot
and his family to flee,


20:52.563 --> 20:55.065
and it’s urgent for us too.


20:55.065 --> 20:58.000
We need to be prepared.


20:59.112 --> 21:03.992
We can prepare, for instance,
if we live in an earthquake zone


21:03.992 --> 21:08.245
by having our houses
built earthquake-proof.


21:08.245 --> 21:10.247
It costs more


21:10.247 --> 21:13.709
—more effort, more time
involved preparing the house—


21:13.708 --> 21:15.711
but when an earthquake hits,


21:15.712 --> 21:19.000
then we are
better prepared to survive.


21:20.925 --> 21:23.177
Revelation refers
to “the four angels who”


21:23.177 --> 21:26.180
have prepared the hour,


21:26.180 --> 21:30.685
or “have been prepared for the hour
and day and month and year,”


21:30.685 --> 21:35.648
units of time that we can understand.
—Revelation 9:14, 15.


21:35.648 --> 21:40.276
Seeing how prophecies
were fulfilled at specific times


21:40.277 --> 21:45.115
should inspire faith
in the God of “times and seasons”


21:45.115 --> 21:47.117
and in his Word.


21:47.117 --> 21:51.497
Soon the angels will let loose
the four winds of destruction.


21:51.497 --> 21:53.707
Are we ready?


21:53.707 --> 21:58.129
Jehovah is a perfect Timekeeper.


21:58.128 --> 22:00.631
Do we make good use
of what we perceive as time


22:00.632 --> 22:04.135
by attending meetings,
reading the Bible daily


22:04.135 --> 22:08.055
—even after Gilead graduation—


22:08.055 --> 22:10.808
going out in field ministry?


22:10.808 --> 22:15.605
Whereas, it is appropriate to take time
for leisure and other activities,


22:15.605 --> 22:19.150
it is good
not to waste time


22:19.150 --> 22:21.443
but keep the balance.


22:21.443 --> 22:23.445
If we use time wisely


22:23.445 --> 22:27.408
—buying it out
by giving priority to spiritual things


22:27.408 --> 22:31.745
and sacrifice less important time
as a payment, so to say—


22:31.745 --> 22:33.830
then we will see
the promise fulfilled


22:33.830 --> 22:37.460
to live forever
and ever and ever.


22:37.460 --> 22:40.503
No more need, then,
to worry about time.


22:40.503 --> 22:43.756
But now is the time to conclude my talk,


22:43.757 --> 22:46.000
so I would not go overtime.


23:10.200 --> 23:12.995
Thank you very much, Brother Lösch.


23:12.995 --> 23:15.288
We thoroughly enjoyed that,


23:15.288 --> 23:19.793
